&gt; --- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com, John Lekashman&lt;lekash@...&gt;  wrote:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; This is not a simple question.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; 1. No.  - There are robots.txt, and prohibited segments, you cannot get at.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; 2. No.  - There are aspects of the web that are deep, behind databases,
&gt;&gt; that heritrix is not designed to hit.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; 3. No. - There are video formats that are problematic to get through
&gt;&gt; normal web download, so it can&#39;t get them.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; And so on.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; That said, yes, it can crawl everywhere.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; The configuration you use is a bunch of machines, where bunch is defined
&gt;&gt; as as many as you can afford.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Expect about 150K worth of hardware, to crawl 10B sites in 2 months.
&gt;&gt; Some good fast 4 core processor, 32G or more memory, maybe 8T - 16T disk
&gt;&gt; on each of 20 - 40 systems.
&gt;&gt; If you want to go faster, scale up your systems.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Set up a hash mapped crawl config, use some seedlist that most interests
&gt;&gt; you, and go.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; I&#39;ve done this a few dozen times, building archive sets.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Maybe I&#39;ll go write a FAQ for it, Gordon says I should.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; John
